cal and scientific works, halakhic literature, and folktales, Idelson-Shein unfolds the myriad ways in which eighteenth-century Jews imagined the "exotic Other" and how the evolving discourse of racial difference played into the construction of their own identities. Difference of a Different Kind offers an invaluable view into the ways new religious, cultural, and racial identities were imagined and formed at the outset of modernity.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aDifference (Philosophy)xHistoryy17th century. 0aDifference (Philosophy)xHistoryy18th century. 0aDifference (Psychology)xHistoryy17th century. 0aDifference (Psychology)xHistoryy18th century. 0aJews, EuropeanxRace identityxHistoryy17th century. 0aJews, EuropeanxRace identityxHistoryy18th century. 0aRace awarenesszEuropexHistoryy17th century. 0aRace awarenesszEuropexHistoryy18th century. 4aReligious Studies. 7aRELIGION / Judaism / History.2bisacsh  aEuropean History.  aHistory.  aJewish Studies.  aReligion.  aReligious Studies.  aWorld History.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Pennsylvania Press Complete Package 2014-2015z978311066593240uhttps://doi.org/10.9783/978081220970940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780812209709423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780812209709.jpg  a978-3-11-066593-2  University of Pennsylvania Press Complete Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK